WEBVTT

00:10.136 --> 00:14.220
And Dinerral was more

00:14.348 --> 00:16.760
than just a big brother to me.

00:17.476 --> 00:20.263
He was the only father figure

00:20.396 --> 00:22.853
I've ever known.

00:23.858 --> 00:26.315
He was always there for me.

00:27.862 --> 00:30.774
He was always the highlight of my life.

00:33.201 --> 00:36.534
I can remember
my high—school graduation

00:37.872 --> 00:40.830
when he lied and told me
that he couldn't make it.

00:42.585 --> 00:45.122
l was so upset with him,

00:45.630 --> 00:47.495
to walk outside

00:48.174 --> 00:50.631
and to find him

00:50.760 --> 00:54.378
and the rest of my Hot 8 brothers
standing in the corner

00:55.097 --> 00:57.759
ready to strike a beat for me.

00:57.892 --> 01:00.224
And he played.

01:00.353 --> 01:02.264
And he gave me and my class

01:02.396 --> 01:05.888
the best graduation second line ever.

01:08.444 --> 01:10.435
He was all I had.

01:12.907 --> 01:15.068
(Sobbing)

01:15.201 --> 01:19.570
Who's gonna be there for me now?

01:20.581 --> 01:23.493
— (Man) Take your time, baby.
— (Sobbing)

01:23.626 --> 01:25.617
(Man) Touch her, Lord.

01:26.712 --> 01:29.419
(Nakita sobbing) Oh God.

01:37.098 --> 01:40.340
Those family members
who wish to take their parting,

01:40.476 --> 01:44.185
- you may do so.
— (Organ playing)

01:44.313 --> 01:46.520
(Man) It's gonna be all right.

01:58.244 --> 02:00.326
- Bennie.
— Hey Antoine.

02:00.454 --> 02:04.242
— I don't know what to say, brah.
- Nothing to say, man.

02:14.844 --> 02:17.506
(J‘ Playing What A Friend We Have In Jesus)

04:06.455 --> 04:07.991
(Woman) All right.

06:13.457 --> 06:15.448
(Woman) And the nature
of Mr. Weyman's passing is,

06:15.584 --> 06:17.324
I know, disturbing to all of us,

06:17.461 --> 06:19.747
particularly with what
many of us have been dealing with

06:19.880 --> 06:21.666
since Hurricane Katrina.

06:22.132 --> 06:25.260
If any of you find yourself
harboring any harmful thoughts

06:25.386 --> 06:29.129
or feel yourselves to be depressed
or feel any anxiety at all,

06:29.265 --> 06:33.133
I want you to bring those feelings
to Dr. Stecklow and her counseling team

06:33.269 --> 06:35.305
or to your regular school counselors

06:35.437 --> 06:38.144
or to any teacher
with whom you feel comfortable.

06:38.274 --> 06:41.641
Students should now proceed
to your regular third—period classes.

06:41.777 --> 06:43.984
(Students chattering)

06:46.323 --> 06:48.314
(Boy) I heard that his wife left him.

06:48.450 --> 06:50.486
(Boy #2) He took pills.
Do you know what he took?

06:50.619 --> 06:52.701
(Boy #1) No, he shot himself.

07:01.130 --> 07:04.418
Sofia, this is especially
hard for you, I know.

07:04.550 --> 07:07.417
— Um...
— If you need to talk, I'm here.

07:29.450 --> 07:31.566
(School bell rings)

07:34.788 --> 07:36.494
It was them niggas
from Robertson and Touro.

07:36.624 --> 07:39.832
They were beefing with his brothers
and seen him come through,

07:39.960 --> 07:41.666
lit his ass up.

07:41.795 --> 07:44.457
- I heard he threw shots first.
— Tristan ain't had no gun, man.

07:44.590 --> 07:46.296
- I seen it.
— You saw his gun?

07:46.425 --> 07:49.007
(Batiste) OK, OK, listen up now.

07:49.136 --> 07:51.297
Listen up.

07:51.430 --> 07:54.046
— Where's Mr. Lecoeur?
— Went down to the office.

07:54.183 --> 07:57.141
He gonna bust some heads,
find out why the instruments ain't coming.

07:57.269 --> 07:59.601
All right, well,
why don't y'all take y'all places?

07:59.730 --> 08:02.142
- All right?
— We ain't supposed to be doing nothing.

08:02.274 --> 08:04.481
— Yes, you are. Take your place. Sit down.
— Nah.

08:04.610 --> 08:06.692
l'm—a deal with you later.
Sit down.

08:06.820 --> 08:08.526
All right, listen.

08:08.656 --> 08:13.741
It's time for a little music appreciation.
Y'all listen much to Louis Armst...

08:13.869 --> 08:16.076
(Class) Ooh!

08:18.832 --> 08:20.743
Y'all listen much to Louis Armstrong?

08:20.876 --> 08:22.958
Mr. Lecoeur said we ain't gonna
do nothing today 'cause of Tristan.

08:23.087 --> 08:25.373
— What happened to Tristan?
— He got shot.

08:26.507 --> 08:28.418
- He got shot?
— He's in the hospital.

08:28.550 --> 08:31.462
Tristan was second snare drummer,
and me — l was third.

08:31.595 --> 08:33.381
So I'm second now, right?

08:33.514 --> 08:35.425
Fool, you ain't even got no instrument.

08:35.557 --> 08:39.721
I'm just saying when | get me one.
Mr. Batiste, I am second now, right?

08:40.896 --> 08:42.887
Go take y'all seats.

08:44.525 --> 08:46.811
Accused of murder
and attempted murder

08:46.944 --> 08:49.777
on the Danziger Bridge
in the days after Katrina,

08:49.905 --> 08:54.444
one by one, seven NOPD officers
turn themselves in to police.

08:54.952 --> 08:56.863
(Reporter) Loved ones say their goodbyes,

08:56.995 --> 08:59.657
as the so—called Danziger 7
turn themselves in

08:59.790 --> 09:01.655
at Orleans Parish Central Lockup.

09:01.792 --> 09:04.374
(Men on TV chanting) NOPD! NOPD!

09:04.878 --> 09:06.288
(Reporter) Seven New Orleans
police officers...

09:06.422 --> 09:08.162
Damn, they indicted all seven.

09:08.298 --> 09:10.004
lf Eddie can convict any of them,

09:10.134 --> 09:12.045
you're gonna follow
with one hell of a civil case.

09:12.177 --> 09:16.762
Yeah, my Danziger file
suddenly has all kind of potential.

09:16.890 --> 09:18.426
This one not so much.

09:18.559 --> 09:19.719
— Abreu?
— Yeah.

09:19.852 --> 09:22.013
Guess I'll call the guy,
tell him what I learned,

09:22.146 --> 09:24.387
give him the number
for the Loyola law clinic.

09:24.523 --> 09:26.434
— Or he can call an investigator.
- Yeah.

09:26.567 --> 09:28.979
But you have enough on your plate.

09:29.987 --> 09:32.228
You're right. I know.

09:32.364 --> 09:34.571
(J‘ Jazz on radio)

09:40.914 --> 09:42.654
(Knock on door)

09:42.791 --> 09:45.373
— Can I help you?
— Safety and permit inspector.

09:45.919 --> 09:48.911
— I didn't call for no inspections.
— No, I'm just canvassing,

09:49.047 --> 09:50.912
looking to see where folks are back

09:51.049 --> 09:53.540
and that everything is
right with the paper.

09:54.511 --> 09:57.844
— That's a new installation, isn't it?
- It all works fine.

09:57.973 --> 10:00.680
Yeah, that's good to hear,
but I didn't see any permit posted.

10:00.809 --> 10:02.674
Don't need no permit.

10:02.811 --> 10:05.553
My pipes work just fine.

10:08.650 --> 10:11.027
— and they turned me back on.
- But this is new work -

10:11.153 --> 10:14.737
new pipes, new commode.
Until you get a state—licensed plumber

10:14.865 --> 10:17.447
to sign off on this work
and get the proper permits,

10:17.576 --> 10:19.908
I'm gonna have to
shut the water off at the street.

10:20.037 --> 10:22.528
I'm out here living hand—to—mouth,
day to day.

10:22.664 --> 10:25.121
Now you're gonna make me pay again

10:25.250 --> 10:27.627
for work I've already done?

10:27.753 --> 10:31.496
- I don't make the ordinances, sir.
— The whole fucking city goes undenNater

10:31.632 --> 10:34.544
and y'all carry on like
it's business as usual.

10:34.676 --> 10:37.133
Now I'm out here on my own
getting shit done.

10:37.262 --> 10:39.218
Don't that count for nothing
with you people?

10:39.348 --> 10:41.339
Sorry, sir.

10:46.063 --> 10:47.178
(Man) Roasted capon...

10:47.314 --> 10:49.896
— Thank you.
— He'll be with you in a moment.

10:50.025 --> 10:51.936
(Man) ...the thigh is stuffed with the truffle.

10:52.069 --> 10:54.560
— The amuse tonight is Spanish mackerel...
— (Whispering)

10:54.696 --> 10:57.108
...with clementine puree,
pickled cranberry and lemon pepper.

11:03.997 --> 11:06.579
— Chef.
— Chef, thank you so much for seeing me.

11:06.708 --> 11:09.950
| just felt the need to apologize to you
and say I'm sorry.

11:10.087 --> 11:12.578
You made things happen for me here
and I fucked it up.

11:12.714 --> 11:15.842
l embarrassed you.
You gave me an amazing break

11:18.345 --> 11:20.427
And ljust... Well, | behaved like a maniac.

11:20.556 --> 11:22.592
There's no excuse.

11:23.058 --> 11:25.390
Did you throw the drink
and the glass or just the drink?

11:25.519 --> 11:27.680
Oh God, no. Just the drink.

11:27.813 --> 11:30.600
—Ammdmﬂ
— Pretty much.

11:31.149 --> 11:33.811
Sazerac — nice touch.

11:34.945 --> 11:36.856
Well, it seemed appropriate.

11:36.989 --> 11:39.526
Listen, | read the article.
Everybody read the article.

11:39.658 --> 11:42.650
— The guy was totally out of line.
— Well, no excuse though, no excuse.

11:42.786 --> 11:45.869
— Listen, go talk to Eric.
- Ripert? Eric Ripert?

11:45.998 --> 11:48.580
Yeah, you know, he's a Buddhist.
He's all into forgiveness.

11:48.709 --> 11:50.495
— He'll take care of you.
- Are you serious?

11:50.627 --> 11:53.494
Yeah. And whatever you do, stop throwing
drinks in people's faces, will you?

11:53.630 --> 11:54.881
- Of course.
— All right, I gotta run.

11:55.007 --> 11:57.965
— I'll see you. Take care.
— Thank you so much, Chef.

12:17.779 --> 12:20.646
Oh, we gotta keep Ballzack on
the track list, let the West Bank represent.

12:21.909 --> 12:23.900
Maybe a draw for the college crowd.

12:25.037 --> 12:28.700
I don't know.
But Miz Tee, Katey, Big Freedia —

12:28.832 --> 12:31.869
it's a good lineup of fresh cuts.
We'll move some units locally.

12:32.002 --> 12:33.117
— Yeah.
— But, Davis,

12:33.253 --> 12:35.790
there's nothing here
that can go national.

12:36.798 --> 12:38.709
(lnhales)

12:38.842 --> 12:41.879
What? Wayne? Juvie?

12:42.971 --> 12:45.462
— You think you can rope them?
— Mystikal?

12:45.599 --> 12:47.214
— I thought you said he was in jail.
— He is.

12:47.351 --> 12:49.433
I'm just hoping he left
a track or two behind

12:49.561 --> 12:51.768
— before he went away.
- Doubtful.

12:54.816 --> 12:56.602
What was that other
young man's name —

12:56.735 --> 12:58.771
the one that you were playing
for me in the car, Davis?

12:58.904 --> 13:00.895
What, the Big Tymers cut?
Mannie Fresh?

13:01.031 --> 13:04.239
You might have a shot with Mannie.
I heard he's in town for the holidays.

13:04.368 --> 13:08.156
Settled, then. We shall seek
an appointment with Mr. Fresh.

13:08.288 --> 13:10.529
We?

13:12.125 --> 13:14.912
(Boat horn blows)

13:24.972 --> 13:26.963
(Guitar playing)

13:39.277 --> 13:43.020
You know, the funeral Sunday,
all those musicians who showed up,

13:43.156 --> 13:45.067
made me kind of proud.

13:45.200 --> 13:48.192
I mean, at the end there
outside the church

13:48.328 --> 13:51.786
I felt like I was part of something,
whether you knew him or not.

13:51.915 --> 13:53.906
Yeah, it felt right.

13:55.836 --> 13:58.953
You didn't tell me about what it was like
playing with Shawn Colvin.

13:59.089 --> 14:02.673
— How did that happen?
— She saw me on Frenchmen Street.

14:02.801 --> 14:05.042
She asked me
to come down to sound check

14:05.178 --> 14:07.089
and we worked up a song.

14:08.181 --> 14:11.298
- Very cool.
— At the end of the set

14:11.435 --> 14:13.847
she introduced me to her manager —

14:13.979 --> 14:16.641
— this dude from Austin.
— Austin, huh?

14:16.773 --> 14:19.640
Like he's gonna sign me right up
'cause Shawn tells him so.

14:19.776 --> 14:22.062
— No interest?
- No.

14:26.199 --> 14:28.861
— I gotta sing, I know.
- Notjust sing.

14:28.994 --> 14:33.283
You want to reach for a brass ring,
you gotta write.

14:39.796 --> 14:42.458
(Boat horn blows)

15:02.319 --> 15:04.105
Oh.

15:05.322 --> 15:07.938
Jesus, Mary and Joseph,
this is great.

15:08.075 --> 15:12.284
Same dishes since the '40s,
damn near the same decor too.

15:12.412 --> 15:15.279
| asked to take you to dinner,
I figured August or Bayona,

15:15.415 --> 15:19.158
— something in town.
— Well, to me this is special.

15:21.463 --> 15:23.579
Thing of it is,
what's great about Mosca's

15:23.715 --> 15:26.206
is the same thing New Orleans
struggles with in a way.

15:27.427 --> 15:29.133
— What's that?
— Change.

15:29.262 --> 15:31.344
Nobody wants the city to change,

15:31.473 --> 15:33.464
not ever, not in any way.

15:34.434 --> 15:37.392
French have it.
Americans come downriver with cotton.

15:37.521 --> 15:40.934
They get called "new money trash"
and they gotta build their mansions upriver.

15:41.066 --> 15:43.603
Years later the Standard Oil men
come down here.

15:43.735 --> 15:45.441
Cotton kings stick up their noses.

15:45.570 --> 15:47.652
They don't invite them
to the Mardi Gras balls.

15:47.781 --> 15:51.239
— So the oil money goes to Houston.
- And now?

15:51.993 --> 15:53.733
Now we're a flooded—out wreck,

15:53.870 --> 15:57.033
trying to scratch it out
on whatever tourist dollars are left.

15:57.582 --> 15:59.834
And still if you want to build
anything down here,

15:59.960 --> 16:01.791
change anything,
modernize anything,

16:01.920 --> 16:04.377
you get looked upon as the problem.

16:04.506 --> 16:06.292
That's crazy.

16:06.424 --> 16:08.631
— What's this?
— Oysters Mosca.

16:08.760 --> 16:10.751
Unbelievable.

16:13.181 --> 16:16.298
Mm. But we need to change.
We have to.

16:17.060 --> 16:19.927
And to bring change to New Orleans,
there are a lot of arguments that,

16:20.063 --> 16:22.270
if they can be avoided,
they should be -

16:22.399 --> 16:24.230
arguments that are off—point,

16:24.359 --> 16:28.227
that don't have to do with the actual merits
of what anybody's trying to do.

16:28.363 --> 16:30.979
— No doubt.
— Pop quiz, Nelson.

16:31.116 --> 16:33.653
What's the next step
after demolition and removal?

16:33.785 --> 16:36.948
— We build something.
— Don't get ahead of yourself.

16:43.170 --> 16:44.910
Planning, land use.

16:45.046 --> 16:48.834
And what, Mr. Nelson Hidalgo
of Dallas, Texas,

16:48.967 --> 16:51.549
is your greatest asset to us
when it comes to planning?

16:53.597 --> 16:56.760
Nobody in this town knows
Nelson Hidalgo from a hole in the ground.

16:58.894 --> 17:00.759
Don't sleep on
the chicken a la grande.

17:00.896 --> 17:03.103
The first bite will make you
weep like a baby.

17:03.231 --> 17:05.062
Ooh.

17:20.165 --> 17:22.872
— Sofia, where were you?
— I went for a walk.

17:23.001 --> 17:25.993
l was calling.
lt's ten o'clock at night.

17:26.755 --> 17:30.168
You didn't go to your afterschool internship.
You left your book bag in your locker.

17:30.300 --> 17:33.292
— You had them check my locker?
— Sof, l was worried.

17:34.346 --> 17:36.632
— Where were you?
- Out.

17:37.432 --> 17:39.343
I'm gonna need more
of an answer than that.

17:39.476 --> 17:42.218
Why? l was out.
It's the truth.

17:42.354 --> 17:44.515
I didn't do anything
I'm not supposed to do.

17:44.648 --> 17:46.764
I didn't go anywhere I'm
not supposed to go.

17:46.900 --> 17:49.892
— Sofia.
— It's the truth.

17:50.028 --> 17:52.189
I'm not lying to you.

17:57.577 --> 17:59.818
- (Police radio chatter)
- (Siren whoops)

18:16.972 --> 18:20.009
— Dead as Kelsey's nuts, huh?
- Three shots, semiautomatic.

18:20.141 --> 18:22.177
Homicide's been notified,
but they're backed up,

18:22.310 --> 18:24.050
calling in the guys from home.

18:24.187 --> 18:26.223
It's the first for us.
It's the fourth citywide.

18:26.356 --> 18:28.768
Crazy.
8—10 to dispatch.

18:28.900 --> 18:33.109
- (Woman) Go ahead, 8-10.
— Could you give us an ETA for homicide?

18:33.238 --> 18:34.444
Stand by.

